---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Eyebrow from '../components/Eyebrow.astro';
import CopyButton from '../components/CopyButton.astro';

const installCmd = "set -g @plugin 'bmohan01/tmux-nudge'";

const footerLinks = [
  { href: 'https://github.com/bmohan01/tmux-nudge', label: 'tmux-nudge' },
];
---
<Base
  title="tmux-nudge"
  current="nudge"
  githubHref="https://github.com/bmohan01/tmux-nudge"
  footerLinks={footerLinks}
>
  <section style="padding: 72px 0 48px;">
    <Eyebrow>tmux-nudge</Eyebrow>
    <h1 style="font-family: var(--font-heading); font-weight: var(--font-heading-weight); font-size: clamp(36px, 4.6vw, 60px); line-height: 1.1; letter-spacing: -0.015em; margin: 0; margin-left: -0.05em; max-width: 22ch;">The pane that needs you, blinking</h1>
    <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.65; max-width: 62ch; margin: 24px 0 0; color: var(--color-text);">
      A tmux plugin that nudges you when a pane needs a human — by blinking a label on the pane and its entry in the status bar. Anything can nudge you: a finished shell script, an idle build, or an AI coding agent waiting for your response.
    </p>
    <div style="display: flex; gap: 12px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-top: 28px;">
      <a href="https://github.com/bmohan01/tmux-nudge" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="btn btn-primary" style="white-space: nowrap;">View on GitHub ↗</a>
      <a href="#install" class="btn btn-secondary" style="white-space: nowrap;">Install</a>
    </div>
    <figure style="margin: 44px 0 0;">
      <img src="/nudge-demo.gif" alt="tmux-nudge blinking a label on a pane and its status-bar entry while a pane waits for a human, then auto-clearing when viewed" loading="lazy" width="960" height="581" style="display: block; width: 100%; height: auto; border: 1px solid var(--color-divider); border-radius: var(--radius-md); box-shadow: var(--shadow-md);" />
      <figcaption style="margin-top: 12px; font-size: 13px; color: var(--color-text); opacity: 0.6;">A pane demanding attention — blinking until you look, then auto-clearing.</figcaption>
    </figure>
  </section>

  <hr class="hr" />

  <section style="padding: 48px 0;">
    <h2 style="font-family: var(--font-heading); font-weight: var(--font-heading-weight); font-size: 26px; margin: 0 0 14px;">Why</h2>
    <p style="font-size: 15.5px; line-height: 1.65; max-width: 64ch; margin: 0; color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-text) 78%, transparent);">
      Generic completion notifiers only know "the process stopped" — they can't tell done from waiting for input, and modern AI-agent TUIs redraw constantly, so silence/activity monitoring misfires on them. AI-agent indicators read hooks and get precise state, but are AI-only, use static border colours, and can't style individual panes independently. tmux-nudge unifies both behind one renderer: pluggable trigger sources feed a single "make this pane demand attention" engine, so the visual treatment is identical no matter what triggered it.
    </p>
  </section>

  <hr class="hr" />

  <section style="padding: 48px 0;">
    <h2 style="font-family: var(--font-heading); font-weight: var(--font-heading-weight); font-size: 26px; margin: 0 0 24px;">Trigger sources</h2>
    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(3, minmax(0,1fr)); gap: 16px; margin-bottom: 32px;">
      <div class="card elev-sm">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px;">
          <span style="width: 8px; height: 8px; border-radius: 50%; background: var(--color-accent); animation: tk-blink 1s steps(1) infinite;"></span>
          <p class="card-kicker" style="margin: 0;">AI harness hook</p>
        </div>
        <p class="card-body">nudge hook from Claude Code, Codex or Kiro CLI — precise needs-input / done / error state.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card elev-sm">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px;">
          <span style="width: 8px; height: 8px; border-radius: 50%; background: var(--color-accent); animation: tk-blink 1s steps(1) infinite; animation-delay: 0.3s;"></span>
          <p class="card-kicker" style="margin: 0;">Shell completion</p>
        </div>
        <p class="card-body">A precmd hook in zsh/bash — any long-running command nudges its pane on completion.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card elev-sm">
        <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px;">
          <span style="width: 8px; height: 8px; border-radius: 50%; background: var(--color-accent); animation: tk-blink 1s steps(1) infinite; animation-delay: 0.6s;"></span>
          <p class="card-kicker" style="margin: 0;">Manual / scripts</p>
        </div>
        <p class="card-body">nudge on flags anything from anywhere — a plain CLI, no integration required.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div style="background: var(--color-surface); border: 1px solid var(--color-divider); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: 18px 20px; display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 14px; flex-wrap: wrap;">
      <span style="width: 9px; height: 9px; border-radius: 50%; background: #e0a940; flex: none; animation: tk-blink 1s steps(1) infinite;"></span>
      <span style="font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Consolas, monospace; font-size: 13.5px; color: var(--color-text);">● tmux-nudge — needs you</span>
      <span style="margin-left: auto; font-size: 13px; color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-text) 55%, transparent);">pane border label; the window's status-bar entry blinks too, until you look</span>
    </div>
    <p style="font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.6; margin-top: 16px; color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-text) 62%, transparent); max-width: 64ch;">A small daemon animates the blink and auto-clears any flagged pane the moment you view it. It starts on the first nudge and exits when none remain.</p>
  </section>

  <hr class="hr" />

  <section style="padding: 48px 0;">
    <h2 style="font-family: var(--font-heading); font-weight: var(--font-heading-weight); font-size: 26px; margin: 0 0 18px;">CLI</h2>
    <pre style="background: var(--color-surface); border: 1px solid var(--color-divider); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: 16px 18px; margin: 0; overflow-x: auto; font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Consolas, monospace; font-size: 13px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text); max-width: 620px;">nudge init                      # set up the renderer; saves your config
nudge install                   # wire shell + Claude + Kiro integrations
nudge uninstall                 # fully reverse init; restores your config
nudge on  [-t pane] [-s state]  # state: needs-input | done | error
nudge off [-t pane]
nudge status</pre>
  </section>

  <hr class="hr" />

  <section id="install" style="padding: 48px 0 80px;">
    <Eyebrow>Install</Eyebrow>
    <h2 style="font-family: var(--font-heading); font-weight: var(--font-heading-weight); font-size: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px;">TPM (recommended)</h2>
    <p style="font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.65; margin: 0 0 16px; color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--color-text) 78%, transparent); max-width: 62ch;">Add one line and press prefix + I. On first load tmux-nudge also auto-wires the shell + Claude Code + Kiro CLI integrations for whatever you have installed.</p>
    <pre style="background: var(--color-surface); border: 1px solid var(--color-divider); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: 16px 18px; margin: 0; overflow-x: auto; font-family: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Consolas, monospace; font-size: 13px; line-height: 1.6; color: var(--color-text); max-width: 520px;">set -g @plugin 'bmohan01/tmux-nudge'</pre>
    <CopyButton command={installCmd} />

    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0,1fr)); gap: 16px; margin-top: 32px;">
      <div class="card">
        <p class="card-kicker">Config</p>
        <p class="card-body">Colours, labels, blink interval and clear mode are all tmux options — set them before tmux-nudge loads. Any option can be overridden per-invocation with a matching NUDGE_* env var.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <p class="card-kicker">Any harness</p>
        <p class="card-body">Adding a harness means pointing its event config at "nudge hook &lt;state&gt;" — no new code. Config generators print ready-to-paste snippets for Claude, Codex and Kiro.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <style is:global>
    @keyframes tk-blink { 0%, 49% { opacity: 1; } 50%, 100% { opacity: 0.25; } }
  </style>
</Base>
